---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Repl from '../../../../components/Repl';
import SchemeRepl from '../../../../components/SchemeRepl';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="Proofs Ch.4 — Mathematical Induction" favicon="✎">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/proof-writing/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to proofs</a>

    <h1>Mathematical Induction</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Jim Hefferon · GFDL + CC BY-SA 2.5 · <a href="https://hefferon.net/">Introduction to Proofs</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Mathematical induction</strong> proves a statement for all natural numbers. Prove it for n=0 (the base case). Then prove: if it holds for n=k, it holds for n=k+1 (the inductive step). The two together guarantee it holds everywhere.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Domino chain -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 120" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Domino 0 (falling) -->
        <rect x="30" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="#4ade80" stroke-width="1.5" transform="rotate(15, 38, 80)"/>
        <text x="38" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="#4ade80" font-size="10">base</text>
        <!-- Domino 1 -->
        <rect x="80" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.5" transform="rotate(10, 88, 80)"/>
        <text x="88" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">k=1</text>
        <!-- Domino 2 -->
        <rect x="130" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.5" transform="rotate(5, 138, 80)"/>
        <text x="138" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">k=2</text>
        <!-- Domino 3 -->
        <rect x="180" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="188" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">k=3</text>
        <!-- Domino 4 -->
        <rect x="230" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <!-- Domino 5 -->
        <rect x="280" y="20" width="16" height="60" rx="2" fill="none" stroke="#71717a" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-opacity="0.45"/>
        <!-- Dots -->
        <text x="340" y="55" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="16" fill-opacity="0.3">...</text>
        <!-- Arrow from base -->
        <path d="M 50 40 Q 65 30 78 35" fill="none" stroke="#4ade80" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
        <polygon points="76,32 82,35 77,39" fill="#4ade80" fill-opacity="0.5"/>
        <!-- Caption -->
        <text x="200" y="115" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.3">Each domino knocks down the next. The base case starts the chain.</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Sum formula -->
    <h3>Example: sum of first n natural numbers</h3>
    <p>Claim: 1 + 2 + ... + n = n(n+1)/2 for all n at least 1. Base case: n=1 gives 1 = 1*2/2, which checks. Inductive step: assume it holds for k, then 1 + ... + k + (k+1) = k(k+1)/2 + (k+1) = (k+1)(k+2)/2. Done.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Induction: 1 + 2 + ... + n = n(n+1)/2

(define (sum-to n)
  (if (= n 0) 0
      (+ n (sum-to (- n 1)))))

(define (formula n) (/ (* n (+ n 1)) 2))

; Verify for many values of n
(define (verify n)
  (display "n=") (display n)
  (display "  sum=") (display (sum-to n))
  (display "  formula=") (display (formula n))
  (display "  match? ") (display (= (sum-to n) (formula n)))
  (newline))

(verify 1)
(verify 5)
(verify 10)
(verify 50)
(verify 100)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Induction: 1 + 2 + ... + n = n*(n+1)//2
for n in [1, 5, 10, 50, 100]:
    actual = sum(range(1, n + 1))
    formula = n * (n + 1) // 2
    print(f"n={n:3d}  sum={actual:5d}  formula={formula:5d}  match={actual == formula}")
`} />
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Inequality -->
    <h3>Example: 2^n > n for all n at least 0</h3>
    <p>Base case: 2^0 = 1 > 0. Inductive step: assume 2^k > k. Then 2^(k+1) = 2 * 2^k > 2k = k + k. For k at least 1, k at least 1, so k + k at least k + 1. So 2^(k+1) > k+1.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Induction: 2^n > n for all n >= 0.

(define (pow2 n)
  (if (= n 0) 1 (* 2 (pow2 (- n 1)))))

(define (check n)
  (display "2^") (display n) (display " = ") (display (pow2 n))
  (display " > ") (display n) (display "? ")
  (display (> (pow2 n) n))
  (newline))

(check 0)
(check 1)
(check 5)
(check 10)
(check 20)
`} />

    <!-- 3. Divisibility -->
    <h3>Example: 3 divides n^3 - n</h3>
    <p>Base case: 0^3 - 0 = 0, and 3 divides 0. Inductive step: assume 3 divides k^3 - k. Then (k+1)^3 - (k+1) = k^3 + 3k^2 + 3k + 1 - k - 1 = (k^3 - k) + 3k^2 + 3k = (k^3 - k) + 3(k^2 + k). The first term is divisible by 3 (inductive hypothesis), the second is clearly divisible by 3. Done.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Induction: 3 divides n^3 - n for all n >= 0.

(define (cube n) (* n n n))

(define (check n)
  (let ((val (- (cube n) n)))
    (display "n=") (display n)
    (display "  n^3-n=") (display val)
    (display "  div by 3? ") (display (= 0 (modulo val 3)))
    (newline)))

(check 0)
(check 1)
(check 2)
(check 5)
(check 10)
(check 17)
`} />

    <!-- 4. Strong induction -->
    <h3>Strong induction</h3>
    <p>In <strong>strong induction</strong>, the inductive hypothesis assumes the statement holds for all values up to k, not just k. Useful when the step from k to k+1 depends on earlier values. Example: every integer at least 2 has a prime factorization. If n is prime, done. If composite, n = a*b where a, b are less than n and at least 2. By strong induction, each has a prime factorization. Combining them gives one for n.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Strong induction: every integer >= 2 has a prime factorization.

(define (factorize n)
  (define (go n d)
    (cond ((<= n 1) (list))
          ((= 0 (modulo n d)) (cons d (go (/ n d) d)))
          (else (go n (+ d 1)))))
  (go n 2))

(define (check n)
  (display n) (display " = ")
  (display (factorize n))
  (newline))

(check 2)
(check 12)
(check 30)
(check 97)
(check 360)
`} />


